66    /**
67    * An abstract class that defines our requirements for manipulating dates,
68    * without tying down a particular implementation.
69    * <P>
70    * Requirement 1 : match at least what Excel does for dates;
71    * Requirement 2 : the date represented by the class is immutable;
72    * <P>
73    * Why not just use java.util.Date? We will, when it makes sense. At times,
74    * java.util.Date can be *too* precise - it represents an instant in time,
75    * accurate to 1/1000th of a second (with the date itself depending on the
76    * time-zone). Sometimes we just want to represent a particular day (e.g. 21
77    * January 2015) without concerning ourselves about the time of day, or the
78    * time-zone, or anything else. That's what we've defined SerialDate for.
79    * <P>
80    * You can call getInstance() to get a concrete subclass of SerialDate,
81    * without worrying about the exact implementation.
82    */
